3. Data & indexing subsystem (thick version)
3.1 Ingestion pipeline
Pipeline stages (each a pure function + CLI entrypoint):

PDF extraction

Use pdfminer / pymupdf to extract pages with layout; keep headings and tables where possible.

Chunking

Paragraph-based with:

Target 800–1200 chars, hard max 1500.

Don’t split table rows or bullet lists.

Tagging (NLP + rules)

Use spaCy/HF NER + your own regex to tag:

Crops (normalized IDs: RICE_IRRIGATED, SORGHUM_RAINFED).

Soil types.

Seasons (Kharif/Rabi/Zaid).

Zones/states.

Add manual overrides for the top 50 high‑value pages.

You end up with corpus_chunks.jsonl as described earlier. Version this with a schema version field.

3.2 Indexing
Dense index: embeddings via your NVIDIA + MiniLM fallback chain; store in Chroma/Qdrant.

Sparse index:

Either BM25 via elasticsearch-lite or Whoosh,

Or, simpler: Postgres tsvector over text + crop_mentions and call that from Python.

Rotations catalog:

Treated as its own “micro‑corpus”:

Dense index for similarity (current crop + soil + irrigation).

Also simple SQL table with columns for zone, soil, irrigation, base_crop for exact filtering.

Expose all of this through a VectorStore and KeywordStore interface so you can swap implementations without touching business logic.

4. Retrieval subsystem: full pipeline
4.1 Query builder (beefed up)
build_retrieval_query(field: FieldMetadata) -> RetrievalQuery

natural_query:
"3-year crop rotation for red loam soil in Southern Karnataka, sprinkler irrigated, current crop barley, Rabi season, break cycle for leaf blight and nutrient depletion."

filters:

zone in [Southern_Karnataka, Karnataka]

soil in [Red_loam]

crop_mentions contains ['Barley', 'Chickpea', 'Finger_millet', 'Sunflower'] (if farmer has preferences)

system_type != ['Monocropping']

hard_constraints:

disallow crops flagged by disease (e.g., avoid leaf‑blight susceptible cereals for Year‑1).

This object is re‑used for both corpus and catalog retrieval.

4.2 Hybrid retrieval + reranker (serious version)
Implementation pattern directly in line with hybrid+cross‑encoder best practices:

Dense retrieval (bi‑encoder)

vector search on full corpus: top 40 chunks.

Sparse retrieval (BM25/FTS)

keyword search on text: top 40 chunks.

Merge & scoring

Union by id.

For each chunk:

score = 0.6 * dense_score_norm + 0.4 * sparse_score_norm.

Cross‑encoder reranking

Take top 40 by combined score.

Run a cross‑encoder (e.g., ms-marco-MiniLM-L12) on (query, chunk_text) pairs.

Get rerank score, reorder, take top 8.

Same pattern applied to rotations_catalog, but with:

Strict filters for zone/soil/irrigation/current crop.

Smaller K (dense top 10 + sparse top 10 → rerank top 5).

This is your “lats and back” of the bodybuilder: it’s what separates toy RAG from serious retrieval.

5. Reasoning subsystem: more muscle & control
5.1 Domain scoring before LLM
Before calling the LLM, you pre‑score candidate rotations:

score_rotation(rotation, field, market_data, rainfall_forecast) -> RotationScore

Compute:

profit_score – normalized expected 3‑year gross margin band using:

median yields from literature,

price distributions (you can hardcode for now, wire to an API later).

soil_health_score – based on:

legume years present,

crop family diversity,

root depth diversity,

use of green manures.

water_risk_score – function of:

total irrigation requirement vs local water reliability,

rainfall forecast class.

pest_break_score – whether sequence breaks primary pest/disease cycles from input.

farmer_preference_score – if farmer gives “no tobacco”, “prefers pulses”, etc.

You then feed the top 3–5 scored candidates into the LLM and tell it:

“You must choose 1–3 rotation plans and justify trade‑offs given these scores and the evidence chunks.”

So the LLM is doing multi‑criteria reasoning on top of your deterministic engine, not inventing rotations from scratch.

5.2 Two‑stage generation
Plan JSON stage

Ultra chain: get only JSON with exact schema.

If you want full bodybuilder: add LLM‑as‑judge self‑check:

After plan is produced, call a lightweight model to verify:

Are all crops supported by at least one evidence chunk?

Are there obvious agronomic contradictions?

If fail → either auto‑retry with different samples or downgrade confidence.

Narrative stage (HTML/text)

Fast chain: convert JSON + evidence into narratives in English (for UI) and Hindi (your existing explainer).

This lets you re‑phrase without touching the core JSON.

6. Serving subsystem: API + multi‑tenant hardening
Even if hackathon, design like it’ll be reused:

API:

POST /api/v1/crop-plan – main.

GET /api/v1/sources/{plan_id} – fetch chunks and PDFs behind a plan.

POST /api/v1/feedback – thumbs up/down, 1–5 rating, comment.

GET /api/v1/metrics/summary – basic dashboard for judges.

Auth:

Simple API key header or JWT, but structure code so you can drop it if not needed in demo.

Rate limiting:

In‑memory limiter (per IP/field) so you don’t DDOS your NIM key on demo day.

7. Evaluation & CI/CD subsystem (this is what blows judges’ minds)
You don’t just “hope” it works; you show tests.

7.1 Golden dataset
Build a small but sharp golden set:

30–50 real/pseudo‑real fields:

mix of crops, soils, irrigated/rainfed, zones.

For each: a “reference” 3‑year rotation (derived from ICAR tables or experts).

Store as eval/golden_crop_plan.jsonl.

7.2 Metrics you track
Use standard RAG metrics, not vague claims:

Retrieval:

context_precision@k – proportion of retrieved chunks actually containing relevant info.

context_recall@k – did retrieval capture all gold supporting docs?

Answer/plan:

Faithfulness / groundedness – are all claims supported by retrieved context?

Relevance – does the plan answer the field’s problem?

Rotation quality – domain metric:

legume presence,

no same crop family repeated 3 years,

water balance acceptable.

Automate these with LLM‑as‑judge + some hard agronomic rules. Use something like RAGAS/DeepEval style pipeline, but keep it minimal.

7.3 CI/CD gate
On each PR:

Run unit + integration tests.

Run RAG eval on golden set (maybe only on a subset).

Fail pipeline if:

Retrieval precision drops below threshold.

Faithfulness score drops below e.g. 0.8.

Domain rotation quality violations increase.

This is “bodybuilder” level discipline; practically no hackathon team will have this.

8. Observability subsystem: see every muscle move
Borrow patterns from modern AI observability guides:

Logs:

Structured logs per request: request id, engine used, top chunk ids, latency per stage.

Metrics (Prometheus):

rag_request_latency_seconds{stage="retrieval"}.

rag_retrieval_zero_hit_total.

rag_fallback_model_count{model="devstral"}.

rag_answer_faithfulness_score_bucket.

Traces (OpenTelemetry):

Span for: ingestion → retrieval → rerank → LLM → post‑processing.

Dashboards (Grafana/LangSmith/etc.):

p95 latency, model usage, hallucination rate, NIM cost per day.

Even in a hackathon, you can show a simple Grafana board or just logs + a small HTML dashboard. Judges eat this up because it screams “production mindset”